      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How does BMI change with age?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The BMI formula and standard WHO thresholds do not change with age, but interpretation differs. Older adults (65+) tend to lose muscle and gain fat without BMI changing much. Some geriatric guidelines suggest BMI 23-27 is acceptable for adults over 65, and BMI below 23 may indicate frailty risk. This calculator shows age-specific notes when you enter your age." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How is body fat percentage estimated from BMI?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "This calculator uses the Deurenberg formula (1991): BF% = 1.20 × BMI + 0.23 × Age - 10.8 × Sex - 5.4 (where Sex = 1 for males, 0 for females). It requires age and sex in addition to BMI. The estimate has a margin of error of ±3-5% and is not as accurate as DEXA scanning or hydrostatic weighing, but provides a useful indication." } }
    ]
